[5] Bolivia
Date: Sun 26 Apr 2020
Source: ProMED-ESP Vol 10, issue 105 from Debate 24 Apr [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
https://www.debate.com.mx/mundo/Bolivia-registra-casos-de-sarampion-tras-20-anos-de-silencio-epidemiologico-20200424-0175.html


Bolivia recorded at least 2 cases of measles after 20 years of epidemiological silence in the country, confirmed by health authorities -- one in the Santa Cruz region, the most hit by the coronavirus pandemic, and another in Chuquisaca.

The secretary of health of the Governorate of Santa Cruz, Academy Urenda, reported on the detected case of measles in a 29 year old pregnant woman, who was isolated for epidemiological studies. All the necessary containment work is being done, this lady is isolated and is without major symptoms, she was vaccinated, therefore, her symptoms are not serious," Urenda said at a press conference. [See ProMED-mail Measles update (13) 20200426.7269683] The secretary asked the population not to be alarmed and stressed that there is a "very high rate of vaccination", but that "all necessary precautions" are being taken to avoid an epidemiological outbreak.

After learning of the case in Santa Cruz, the director of the Departmental Health Service (Headquarters) in the Bolivian region of Chuquisaca, Martin Maturano, reported another case of measles in that department. Maturano told the media that vaccination will be strengthened in the department, which has about 40 000 doses available to carry out tracking among at-risk populations, such as those under 5 years of age.

In Bolivia the last endemic case of measles was reported in 2000 and then there was an epidemiological silence.

