[7] Philippines (Luzon): decrease in cases
Date: Thu 7 May 2020
Source: Manila Times [abridged, edited]
https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/05/07/news/national/ecq-reduced-measles-cases-expert/723143/


The enhanced community quarantine (ECQ) implemented in Metro Manila and other areas in Luzon has lowered the incidence of a measles outbreak in the country, according to an infectious disease expert. Philippine Foundation for Vaccination director Dr Lulu Bravo said several measures imposed to stem the spread of the coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) also reduced the number of measles cases. "With ECQ, there have been dramatic reductions of measles if you compare it on the same time last year [2019]," she added. "It was terrible last year," she said, referring to the 47 871 reported cases of measles, with 632 deaths.

As of February this year [2020], only 189 cases and 10 deaths have been reported in comparison with 8443 and 189 deaths at the same time last year [2019], according to the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies.

"The ECQ did not just reduce the cases of COVID-19, but the projected number for measles, as well. The physical distancing was effective in combating measles, because it is airborne," Bravo said.

[byline: John Eric Mendoza]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Quarantine of the population likely did contribute to dampening virus transmission outside the family unit from those who are currently infected, but a long-term effect of quarantine may be increased transmission if vaccinations are interrupted by the COVID-19 pandemic. In 2019 when there was a major measles outbreak in the country, the government launched a massive nationwide measles vaccination campaign. Health workers inoculated 5.5 million people, mostly kids. The government hoped to immunize another 15 million by the end of September 2019. The campaign was very effective in stopping the measles outbreak at the time. This increased the immunization rate and likely also contributed to the low prevalence this year. Good news! - Mod.LK

